BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Jacobs School of Music": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/berlin-soiree-2026"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_jacobs_music
X-SOURCE:IU Jacobs School of Music
DTSTART:20260320T180000Z
DTEND:20260320T190000Z
LOCATION:Mendelssohn Remise\, Jägerstr. 51\, 10117 Berlin
GEO:52.514347;13.395066
SUMMARY:Berlin Soirée – A Showcase of Emerging Voices from Indiana Uni
 versity's Jacobs School of Music
DESCRIPTION:Please join us for a classical soirée featuring performances
  by emerging talents from the Indiana University Jacobs School of Music. 
      Enjoy an intimate evening that will showcase the exceptional vocal a
 bilities of IU's rising stars. With a diverse program of timeless works\,
  each performance reflects the dedication\, artistry\, and passion of the
 se gifted young singers. This recital offers a wonderful opportunity to h
 ear the voices of tomorrow as they take the stage today.      This is a f
 ree event. Attendance to this event is capped and decided on a first-come
 \, first-served basis. Please register below.    &#160\;      Meet the Pe
 rformers  Haocheng Du\, Tenor          Tenor Haocheng Du is pursuing a Do
 ctor of Music in Voice Performance degree at the Jacobs School of Music\,
  studying under the guidance of Heidi Grant Murphy. Originally from Wuhan
 \, China\, he completed his undergraduate and graduate studies at the Wuh
 an Conservatory of Music. He studied under Professor Leiming He during hi
 s gradute studies\, his undergradute mentors were Professor Yongxi Chen a
 nd Lecture Jinping Li. Du has earned several accolades\, including being 
 a finalist in the 2023 Hubei Regional Final of the 14th China Golden Bell
  Award for Music and the 10th Hubei Golden Bell Music Award. He also won 
 first place in the Bel Canto Group of the Wuhan Conservatory of Music Cup
  Competition. More recently\, he was a semifinalist in the 2024 China Lit
 tle Golden Bell First National Vocal Arts Exhibition. At IU\, Du performe
 d La Bohème (Rodolfo) in 2025.        Theo Harrah\, Bass          A bass
  from Louisville\, Kentucky\, Theo Harrah is a second-year master's stude
 nt studying under the tutelage of Jane Dutton. His previous credits at Ja
 cobs include the Second Armed Man in The Magic Flute\, Dick Deadeye in H.
 M.S. Pinafore\, Siroco in L'Étoile\, José Tripaldi in Ainadamar\, Frèr
 e Laurent in Roméo et Juliette\, Judge Turpin in Sweeney Todd\, Zuniga i
 n Carmen\, and Sheldon Anapol in the world premiere of The Amazing Advent
 ures of Kavalier &amp\; Clay in collaboration with the Metropolitan Opera
 . Additionally\, he performed in the choruses of Falstaff\, Highway 1\, U
 SA\, Candide\, The Merry Widow\, and The Marriage of Figaro. He has also 
 been featured as a soloist in Mozart's Requiem\, Schütz's Musikalische E
 xequien\, and the Howells Requiem. Outside of Jacobs\, Harrah has been se
 en as Colline in La Bohème and Simone in Gianni Schicchi at the Canto Pr
 ogram\, Dean of the Faculties in Massenet's Cendrillon at Cedar Rapids Op
 era\, and on concert stages worldwide performing everything from Schubert
  to Verdi. In 2024\, he was a finalist in the Meistersinger competition i
 n Graz\, Austria. In 2025\, Harrah was in the Santa Fe Opera apprentice p
 rogram for singers\, where he sang in the choruses of La Bohème and Rigo
 letto and sang the role of Count Ceprano. This summer\, he looks forward 
 to participating in the Merola Opera program in San Francisco\, where he 
 will be singing Lakai in Strauss's Ariadne auf Naxos as well as covering 
 Truffaldino in the same production.        Esther Jo\, Mezzo-Soprano     
      Mezzo-soprano Esther Jo\, from Seoul\, South Korea\, is pursuing an 
 Artist Diploma with a Performance Fellowship and full scholarship under t
 he tutelage of Jane Dutton at the Jacobs School of Music. She also recent
 ly completed her Performer Diploma\, which includes a Performer's Certifi
 cate\, with the fellowship and scholarship. With Indiana University Opera
  Theater\, she has portrayed the title role of Carmen\, Madame de la Halt
 ière in Cendrillon\, La Zia Principessa in Suor Angelica\, and Olga in E
 ugene Onegin. She has also appeared in opera workshops\, performing Reine
  Gertrude in Hamlet\, Giovanna Seymour in Anna Bolena\, and Carmen in Car
 men\, and will perform Charlotte in Werther. Jo was named a finalist in t
 he prestigious Georgina Joshi Foundation Graduate Fellowship Competition.
  She was also selected to participate in a masterclass with Stuart Skelto
 n. She will further expand her artistic career in Europe as a Faculty-Nom
 inated and Competition Winner participant in the Berlin Performance Progr
 am. This summer\, she will join Opera Maine as a Studio Artist\, covering
  Gertrude in Roméo et Juliette\, and performing Khanh in Bound. In Korea
 \, Jo studied under Locky Chung and Su-gil Park\, performing Maddalena in
  Rigoletto (a coproduction of Hanyang University and the Seongdong Cultur
 al Foundation)\, Dorabella in Così fan tutte\, and Dritte Dame in Die Za
 uberflöte\, among other roles. As an alto soloist\, she has appeared in 
 Charpentier's Te Deum\, Vivaldi's Gloria in D Major\, Britten's A Ceremon
 y of Carols\, and Schütz's Die sieben Worte Jesu Christi am Kreuz. She f
 urther refined her artistry through masterclasses with Mutsumi Moteki and
  as a voice fellow at Yewool Music Stage. Jo graduated summa cum laude wi
 th a Bachelor of Music from Hanyang University\, receiving multiple merit
 -based full scholarships\, an exclusive teaching certification\, and rank
 ing among the top three students in the voice department. She continued h
 er studies in the Master of Music program with full scholarship and resea
 rch assistantship.        Brittany Rose Weinstock\, Soprano          Orig
 inally from Los Angeles\, soprano Brittany Rose Weinstock is a Performer'
 s Diploma student at the Indiana University Jacobs School of Music studyi
 ng under Carol Vaness\, where she also earned her Master's degree. She ea
 rned her B.A. from Pepperdine University\, studying under Louise Lofquist
 . This summer\, Ms. Weinstock will be a Resident Artist with Teatro Nuovo
 \, covering Zaida in Il Turco in Italia and study-covering Donna Anna in 
 Don Giovanni. Indiana University performances include the title role in M
 assenet's Cendrillon\, Micaëla in Carmen\, and Helen in The Amazing Adve
 ntures of Kavalier &amp\; Clay\, a co-production with the Metropolitan Op
 era. Previous engagements include Music on Site (Contessa\, Le nozze di F
 igaro)\, Aspen Music Festival (Musetta cover\, La Bohème)\, Central City
  Opera (Anna Maurrant cover\, Street Scene)\, and the Sherrill Milnes Sav
 annah VOICE Festival. Other credits include H.M.S. Pinafore (Josephine)\,
  Into the Woods (Jack's Mother)\, and Le nozze di Figaro (Contessa) with 
 Pepperdine University. Brittany Rose has received recognition in competit
 ions such as the Opera Birmingham Competition (Finalist)\, Camille Colora
 tura Awards (Semi-Finalist)\, NSAL Indiana Vocal Competition (3rd Place)\
 , Carolyn Bailey Argento and Loren L. Zachary Competitions (Finalist)\, a
 nd Laffont Competition (Encouragement Award). Ms. Weinstock is also an av
 id scholar and a 2025-26 recipient of the Georgina Joshi Travel Grant\, w
 hich allowed her to travel to Central Europe to research Jewish Music of 
 the Holocaust.        Samuel Wetzel\, Baritone          Samuel Wetzel is 
 pursuing a Performer Diploma in Solo Performance\, studying with Jane Dut
 ton. Hailing from Erie\, Pennsylvania\, he has most recently sung Count A
 lmaviva in Jacobs' production of Le Nozze di Figaro\, Melisso in Alcina a
 nd the baritone solos in Vaughn Williams' Dona Nobis Pacem with the Unive
 rsity Chorale. He is a regular soloist with the Bloomington Bach Cantata 
 Project\, and performs with local early music ensembles\, most recently p
 erforming BWV 106 with the Second Presbyterian Church of Louisville featu
 ring Guy Fishman. He earned a master's degree from the University of Colo
 rado at Boulder (CU)\, where he sang a number of roles\, including Pa in 
 Mizzy Mazoli's Proving Up\, Ford in Verdi's Falstaff\, Pandolfe in Massen
 et's Cendrillon\, and Marcello in Puccini's La Bohème. He also participa
 ted in the CU New Opera Works Festival\, where he worked with Gene Scheer
  (2024) and Tom Cipullo (2023) to workshop their new operas. He participa
 ted in the Opera Steamboat program\, singing Brundibar in Brundibar. He r
 ecently won the Colorado Bach Ensemble's Annual Competition for Young Art
 ists and performs regularly with them. He earned a bachelor's degree in m
 usic at the Baldwin Wallace Conservatory of Music\, where he sang roles i
 n their operas and participated in the annual Bach Festival.        Allan
  Armstrong\, Faculty PianistFaculty Pianist - Allan Armstrong          Pi
 anist and vocal coach Allan Armstrong is associate professor of music in 
 voice at the Indiana University Jacobs School of Music\, where he special
 izes in art song literature and opera coaching. He is also the official a
 ccompanist of the Metropolitan Opera National Council Auditions for both 
 the Colorado/Wyoming District and the Rocky Mountain Region. From 2017 to
  2020\, he was a postdoctoral scholar and visiting assistant professor in
  chamber and collaborative music at the Jacobs School. He was previously 
 a member of the applied piano faculty at the University of Texas Rio Gran
 de Valley\, where he codirected the nationally award-winning Bravo Opera 
 Company. Armstrong has been a principal production pianist and coach at E
 ugene Opera\, Opera Colorado\, St. Petersburg Opera\, Opera on the Avalon
 \, Sugar Creek Opera\, Tel Aviv Summer Opera Program\, and Opera Tampa. H
 e has taught on the faculty of the Sherrill Milnes Savannah Voice Festiva
 l and the International Vocal Arts Institute\, in Blacksburg\, Virginia. 
 In 2005\, he coached and recorded the newly revised version of Béla Bart
 ók's Bluebeard's Castle under the direction of the composer's son\, Pete
 r Bartók.​ In 2010\, Armstrong was a featured solo pianist in a recita
 l of the complete solo piano works of Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Dav
 id Del Tredici at New York University Steinhardt. Armstrong earned a Doct
 or of Musical Arts in Collaborative Piano degree from the University of C
 olorado Boulder. He also earned a Master of Music degree in Chamber Music
  and a Bachelor of Arts degree from the University of South Florida\, whe
 re he studied with Svetozar Ivanov and Robert Helps. Armstrong holds prof
 essional memberships in the College Music Society and the National Associ
 ation of Teachers of Singing (NATS). In 2019\, he was chosen to participa
 te in the acclaimed NATS Intern Program at the New England Conservatory.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<div id="lw_cal_event_detail_intro" class="l
 w_cal_event_detail_block"><p>    Please join us for a classical soirée f
 eaturing performances by emerging talents from the Indiana University Jac
 obs School of Music.  </p></div><div id="lw_cal_event_detail_description"
  class="lw_cal_event_detail_block"><p>    Enjoy an intimate evening that 
 will showcase the exceptional vocal abilities of IU's rising stars. With 
 a diverse program of timeless works\, each performance reflects the dedic
 ation\, artistry\, and passion of these gifted young singers. This recita
 l offers a wonderful opportunity to hear the voices of tomorrow as they t
 ake the stage today.  </p><hr /><p>    This is a free event. Attendance t
 o this event is capped and decided on a first-come\, first-served basis. 
 <strong>Please register below.</strong></p><p>    &#160\;  </p><h4>    Me
 et the Performers  </h4><div class="lw_accordion"><section class="lw_acco
 rdion_block"><h4 class="lw_accordion_block_title"><button aria-expanded="
 false" type="button">Haocheng Du\, Tenor</button></h4><div class="lw_acco
