 </picture><br /><p>          Samuel Wetzel is pursuing a Performer Diplom
 a in Solo Performance\, studying with Jane Dutton. Hailing from Erie\, Pe
 nnsylvania\, he has most recently sung Count Almaviva in Jacobs' producti
 on of <i>Le Nozze di Figaro\, </i>Melisso in <i>Alcina</i> and the barito
 ne solos in Vaughn Williams' Dona Nobis Pacem with the University Chorale
 . He is a regular soloist with the Bloomington Bach Cantata Project\, and
  performs with local early music ensembles\, most recently performing BWV
  106 with the Second Presbyterian Church of Louisville featuring Guy Fish
 man. He earned a master's degree from the University of Colorado at Bould
 er (CU)\, where he sang a number of roles\, including Pa in Mizzy Mazoli'
 s <i>Proving Up</i>\, Ford in Verdi's <i>Falstaff</i>\, Pandolfe in Masse
 net's <i>Cendrillon</i>\, and Marcello in Puccini's <i>La Bohème</i>. He
  also participated in the CU New Opera Works Festival\, where he worked w
 ith Gene Scheer (2024) and Tom Cipullo (2023) to workshop their new opera
 s. He participated in the Opera Steamboat program\, singing Brundibar in 
 <i>Brundibar. </i>He recently won the Colorado Bach Ensemble's Annual Com
 petition for Young Artists and performs regularly with them. He earned a 
 bachelor's degree in music at the Baldwin Wallace Conservatory of Music\,
  where he sang roles in their operas and participated in the annual Bach 
 Festival.        </p></div></section><section class="lw_accordion_block">
 <h4 class="lw_accordion_block_title"><button aria-expanded="false" type="
 button">Allan Armstrong\, Faculty Pianist</button></h4><div class="lw_acc
 ordion_block_content" aria-hidden="true"><p><picture class="lw_image lw_i
 mage25593  lw_align_left"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://event
 s.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/92/width/200/height/200/25593_armstrong-
