X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199384-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-anke", "IU La Casa Latino Cultural Center": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199384-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-anke"}
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199384-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-anke"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_hamilton_lugar
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School, IU La Casa Latino Cultural Center
DTSTART:20260413T200000Z
DTEND:20260413T210000Z
LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 1060
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Anke Birkenmaier
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Anke Birkenmaier as she presents Circulating Latin America: 
 Ethical Interventions from the Global South.  &#160\;  Recent Latin Ameri
 can literature is circulating widely in translation\, through independent
  and mainstream publishers\, and is winning international awards. This pr
 esentation focuses on two novels\, Karla Suarez's Objetos perdidos and Cl
 audio Piñeiro's Elena sabe\, to assess both the formal strategies and th
 e ethical import of recent writing by Latin American writers\, and the wa
 ys in which they build bridges between local and global political engagem
 ent.Anke Birkenmaier is currently serving as chair of the Spanish and Por
 tuguese department in the College of Arts and Sciences at Indiana Univers
 ity. Birkenmaier is a scholar of modern Caribbean and Latin American lite
 rature and culture\, and in studying these areas she has two major foci. 
 She studies literature in relation to other discourses such as anthropolo
 gy\, looking at the ways in which ideas about culture and race have evolv
 ed over time. Her interest in media and sound studies has also led her to
  explore the ways in which the novel has entered in competition with othe
 r communication media.  &#160\;  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets M
 ondays from February through April\, with faculty and guest speakers enga
 ging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on history\, cultur
 e\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (https:/
 /events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Dr. Anke B
 irkenmaier</strong> as she presents <em><strong>Circulating Latin America
 : Ethical Interventions from the Global South.</strong></em></p><p>  &#16
 0\;</p><p>  Recent Latin American literature is circulating widely in tra
 nslation\, through independent and mainstream publishers\, and is winning
  international awards. This presentation focuses on two novels\, Karla Su
 arez's Objetos perdidos and Claudio Piñeiro's Elena sabe\, to assess bot
 h the formal strategies and the ethical import of recent writing by Latin
  American writers\, and the ways in which they build bridges between loca
 l and global political engagement.</p><p><strong>Anke Birkenmaier</strong
 > is currently serving as chair of the Spanish and Portuguese department 
 in the College of Arts and Sciences at Indiana University. Birkenmaier is
  a scholar of modern Caribbean and Latin American literature and culture\
 , and in studying these areas she has two major foci. She studies literat
 ure in relation to other discourses such as anthropology\, looking at the
  ways in which ideas about culture and race have evolved over time. Her i
 nterest in media and sound studies has also led her to explore the ways i
 n which the novel has entered in competition with other communication med
 ia.<em><br /></em></p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloqui
 um meets Mondays from February through April\, with faculty and guest spe
 akers engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on histor
 y\, culture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the <a href="http
 s://events.iu.edu/clacs/">CLACS Calendar</a> for details.</p><p><picture 
