X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Asian Culture Center": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2139681-taiwan-studies-initiative-milk-tea-month-the-milk"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_asian_culture
X-SOURCE:IU Asian Culture Center, IU Hamilton Lugar School
DTSTART:20260424T160000Z
DTEND:20260424T173000Z
LOCATION:GLOBAL &amp\; INTERNATIONAL STUDIES BUILDING - Room Number: 2067
GEO:39.170002;-86.517492
SUMMARY:Taiwan Studies Initiative Milk Tea Month: The Milk Tea Alliance
DESCRIPTION:Historian Jeffrey Wasserstrom met dozens of dissidents\, incl
 uding Netiwit Chotiphatphaisal\, known for his protests against compulsor
 y Thai military service\; Agnes Chow\, co-founder of a political party no
 w banned in Hong Kong\; and Ye Myint Win (aka Nickey Diamond)\, who fled 
 to Germany from Burma in the early 2020s\, fearing reprisal from the junt
 a for his human rights work. Activists like these three express solidarit
 y with one another online and on the streets\, and sometimes refer to the
 mselves as belonging to the "Milk Tea Alliance\," a nod to their shared o
 pposition to nationalistic Beijing loyalists and the fact that their cult
 ures' iconic drinks contain dairy\, unlike mainland China's traditional t
 ea.  How do these activists\, each facing their unique situations\, find 
 common ground and sustain one another? Wasserstrom traveled globally to i
 nterview members of this loosely constituted alliance\, meeting some in A
 sia and others in exile\, finding them united by democratic values\, shar
 ed concerns over autocrats\, and the rising influence of a common adversa
 ry—the Chinese Communist Party.  During this talk\, Dr. Wasserstrom wil
 l discuss his research with a special focus on Taiwan.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p class="cvGsUA direction-ltr align-start p
 ara-style-body">  Historian Jeffrey Wasserstrom met dozens of dissidents\
 , including Netiwit Chotiphatphaisal\, known for his protests against com
 pulsory Thai military service\; Agnes Chow\, co-founder of a political pa
 rty now banned in Hong Kong\; and Ye Myint Win (aka Nickey Diamond)\, who
  fled to Germany from Burma in the early 2020s\, fearing reprisal from th
 e junta for his human rights work. Activists like these three express sol
 idarity with one another online and on the streets\, and sometimes refer 
 to themselves as belonging to the "Milk Tea Alliance\," a nod to their sh
 ared opposition to nationalistic Beijing loyalists and the fact that thei
 r cultures' iconic drinks contain dairy\, unlike mainland China's traditi
 onal tea.<br /><br />  How do these activists\, each facing their unique 
 situations\, find common ground and sustain one another? Wasserstrom trav
 eled globally to interview members of this loosely constituted alliance\,
  meeting some in Asia and others in exile\, finding them united by democr
 atic values\, shared concerns over autocrats\, and the rising influence o
 f a common adversary—the Chinese Communist Party.</p><p class="cvGsUA d
 irection-ltr align-start para-style-body">  During this talk\, Dr. Wasser
 strom will discuss his research with a special focus on Taiwan.</p>
UID:20260424T160000Z-2238092@events.iu.edu
DTSTAMP:20260313T090025Z
URL:https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2139681-taiwan-studies-initiative-m
 ilk-tea-month-the-milk
CATEGORIES:Culture and languages,Lectures, talks, seminars, and conferences
LAST-MODIFIED:20260313T130025Z
