SUMMARY:US Law and Legal Writing Summer Workshop Application Due
DESCRIPTION:Program OverviewDates: July 13-31\, 2026 (3 weeks)Format: In-
 person at IU Bloomington Maurer School of LawTime: Monday-Friday\, 9:30 A
 M - 2:00 PM  This workshop covers:Legal Research - Master Westlaw/LexisNe
 xis and legal search strategies  Legal Writing - Learn IRAC methodology a
 nd legal memo drafting  Case Analysis - Develop case briefing and synthes
 is skills  Professional Skills - Presentation training and cross-cultural
  legal discourse    Why This Program?International Collaboration  Work al
 ongside undergraduate law students from Pontificia Universidad Católica 
 del Perú (PUCP)\, gaining exposure to comparative legal systems and buil
 ding your international network.Practical Skills  Gain hands-on experienc
 e with the same research and writing techniques used in law school and le
 gal practice.Pathway to Graduate Study  Credits earned may be applied tow
 ard the Master of Legal Studies (MLS) program if you choose to pursue tha
 t degree.  Enrollment OptionsOption 1: For CreditCourse: B504 Introductio
 n to Law: Legal Writing (3 credits)  Tuition: Standard undergraduate rate
  ($1\,229.64 in-state\; $4\,018.56 out-of-state) + $300 programming/activ
 ities fee ($1\,529.64 in-state\; $4\,318.56 out-of-state)  Benefit: Offic
 ial transcript credit\, potential application toward MLS program  Option 
 2: Non-CreditFee: $1\,500 flat rate  Benefit: Certificate of completion\,
  full program access without transcript credit    What You'll LearnWeek 1
 : FoundationsU.S. court structure and jurisdiction  Common Law vs. Civil 
 Law systems  Legal research databases and strategies  Case briefing metho
 dology  Week 2: Legal WritingIRAC analysis framework  Legal memorandum st
 ructure  Citation skills (Bluebook basics)  Peer review and revision stra
 tegies  Week 3: Advanced SkillsInternational and comparative legal resear
 ch  Legal ethics and professional responsibility  Capstone research proje
 ct and presentation    Daily Schedule9:30 AM - 12:00 PM: Main curriculum 
 instruction  12:00 PM - 1:00 PM: Lunch break  1:00 PM - 2:00 PM: Legal En
 glish support  Evenings: Optional cultural and professional activities   
  How to RegisterRegistration Opens: March 1Registration Deadline: Priorit
 y registration: April 30\; Final deadline: June 19Steps to Register:Decid
 e whether you want to enroll for credit (B504) or non-credit  For Credit:
  Complete the pre-registration form\; once permission received\, register
  through standard IU course registration system  Non-Credit: [TBD]  Quest
 ions? Contact: Dr Elisheva Cohen\, ellcohen@iu.edu (mailto:ellcohen@iu.ed
 u)  Who Should Apply?  This program is ideal for Hamilton Lugar School un
 dergraduates who are:Considering law school or legal careers  Interested 
 in policy\, international relations\, or governance  Seeking to build res
 earch and analytical writing skills  Curious about comparative legal syst
 ems  Looking for meaningful international collaboration experience  No pr
 ior legal background required - just curiosity and commitment to intensiv
 e summer learning!
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<h2>  Program Overview</h2><p><strong>Dates:
 </strong> July 13-31\, 2026 (3 weeks)</p><p><strong>Format:</strong> In-p
 erson at IU Bloomington Maurer School of Law</p><p><strong>Time:</strong>
  Monday-Friday\, 9:30 AM - 2:00 PM</p><p>  This workshop covers:</p><ul><
 li><strong>Legal Research</strong> - Master Westlaw/LexisNexis and legal 
 search strategies  </li><li><strong>Legal Writing</strong> - Learn IRAC m
 ethodology and legal memo drafting  </li><li><strong>Case Analysis</stron
 g> - Develop case briefing and synthesis skills  </li><li><strong>Profess
 ional Skills</strong> - Presentation training and cross-cultural legal di
 scourse  </li></ul><h2>  Why This Program?</h2><p><strong>International C
 ollaboration</strong></p><p>  Work alongside undergraduate law students f
 rom Pontificia Universidad Católica del Perú (PUCP)\, gaining exposure 
 to comparative legal systems and building your international network.</p>
 <p><strong>Practical Skills</strong></p><p>  Gain hands-on experience wit
 h the same research and writing techniques used in law school and legal p
 ractice.</p><p><strong>Pathway to Graduate Study</strong></p><p>  Credits
  earned may be applied toward the Master of Legal Studies (MLS) program i
 f you choose to pursue that degree.</p><h2>  Enrollment Options</h2><p><s
 trong>Option 1: For Credit</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Course:</strong> B
 504 Introduction to Law: Legal Writing (3 credits)  </li><li><strong>Tuit
 ion:</strong> Standard undergraduate rate ($1\,229.64 in-state\; $4\,018.
 56 out-of-state) + $300 programming/activities fee ($1\,529.64 in-state\;
  $4\,318.56 out-of-state)  </li><li><strong>Benefit:</strong> Official tr
 anscript credit\, potential application toward MLS program  </li></ul><p>
 <strong>Option 2: Non-Credit</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Fee:</strong> $1
 \,500 flat rate  </li><li><strong>Benefit:</strong> Certificate of comple
 tion\, full program access without transcript credit  </li></ul><h2>  Wha
 t You'll Learn</h2><p><strong>Week 1: Foundations</strong></p><ul><li>U.S
 . court structure and jurisdiction  </li><li>Common Law vs. Civil Law sys
 tems  </li><li>Legal research databases and strategies  </li><li>Case bri
 efing methodology  </li></ul><p><strong>Week 2: Legal Writing</strong></p
 ><ul><li>IRAC analysis framework  </li><li>Legal memorandum structure  </
 li><li>Citation skills (Bluebook basics)  </li><li>Peer review and revisi
 on strategies  </li></ul><p><strong>Week 3: Advanced Skills</strong></p><
 ul><li>International and comparative legal research  </li><li>Legal ethic
 s and professional responsibility  </li><li>Capstone research project and
  presentation  </li></ul><h2>  Daily Schedule</h2><ul><li><strong>9:30 AM
  - 12:00 PM:</strong> Main curriculum instruction  </li><li><strong>12:00
  PM - 1:00 PM:</strong> Lunch break  </li><li><strong>1:00 PM - 2:00 PM:<
 /strong> Legal English support  </li><li><strong>Evenings:</strong> Optio
 nal cultural and professional activities  </li></ul><h2>  How to Register
 </h2><p><strong>Registration Opens:</strong> March 1</p><p><strong>Regist
 ration Deadline:</strong> Priority registration: April 30\; Final deadlin
 e: June 19</p><p><strong>Steps to Register:</strong></p><ol><li>Decide wh
 ether you want to enroll for credit (B504) or non-credit  </li><li><stron
 g>For Credit:</strong> Complete the pre-registration form\; once permissi
 on received\, register through standard IU course registration system  </
 li><li><strong>Non-Credit:</strong> [TBD]  </li></ol><p><strong>Questions
 ?</strong> Contact: Dr Elisheva Cohen\, <a href="mailto:ellcohen@iu.edu">
 ellcohen@iu.edu</a></p><h2>  Who Should Apply?</h2><p>  This program is i
 deal for Hamilton Lugar School undergraduates who are:</p><ul><li>Conside
 ring law school or legal careers  </li><li>Interested in policy\, interna
 tional relations\, or governance  </li><li>Seeking to build research and 
 analytical writing skills  </li><li>Curious about comparative legal syste
 ms  </li><li>Looking for meaningful international collaboration experienc
 e  </li></ul><p><strong>No prior legal background required</strong> - jus
 t curiosity and commitment to intensive summer learning!</p>
